Research Question

Enrique Kike Hernndez is widely regarded for his exceptional postseason performances. While his regular-season statistics are often overlooked compared to other players, this is rightfully so, as his postseason success is what truly stands out. His playoff performances place him among the greatest postseason hitters in recent history. My research aims to investigate the dramatic difference between his regular-season and postseason play, focusing on splits such as RHP vs LHP, home vs away, and fastball vs other pitches. This analysis explores whether Kikes postseason success is a statistical anomaly or if he truly excels under pressure, highlighting his ability to elevate his game when it matters most.

Narrative Text

Reason why I want to investigate this topic: The main reason I chose to investigate Kike Hernndezs postseason performance is to understand what makes him so successful in high-pressure situations. Unlike many players who struggle to replicate their regular-season success in the postseason, Kike consistently performs at an elite level when it matters most. This contrast between his regular-season and postseason statistics presents an unique opportunity to explore how different factorssuch as performance against right-handed vs.left-handed pitchers, home vs.away games, and fastball vs.other pitchesmight explain Kikes remarkable postseason success. By analyzing his performance through these splits, I aim to identify patterns and factors that contribute to his ability to elevate his game in the postseason.

One significant technical challenge: One of the main challenges I faced during this project was merging and organizing data from different sources. Postseason and regular-season data came from separate datasets, and they needed to be carefully cleaned and aligned for accurate comparison. Additionally, finding the right metrics that captured Kikes performance under pressurewhile also filtering out the noiserequired substantial data wrangling. After ensuring the datasets were properly combined and transformed, I was able to conduct a comprehensive analysis comparing Kikes postseason and regular-season stats.

This code imports datasets on Kik Hernndezs regular-season and postseason performances, split by pitcher handedness (LHP vs.RHP), game location (home vs.away), and pitch type (fastballs vs.off-speed). These datasets allow for a comparison of his performance across different conditions, emphasizing his postseason excellence relative to the regular season.

# Combine all the metrics into a single dataframe, adding 'season' and 'condition'
all_metrics <- bind_rows(
  mutate(Kike_regular_lhp, season = "Regular", condition = "Regular LHP"),
  mutate(Kike_regular_rhp, season = "Regular", condition = "Regular RHP"),
  mutate(Kike_regularaway, season = "Regular", condition = "Regular Away"),
  mutate(Kike_regularhome, season = "Regular", condition = "Regular Home"),
  mutate(Kike_postseason_lhp, season = "Postseason", condition = "Postseason LHP"),
  mutate(Kike_postseason_rhp, season = "Postseason", condition = "Postseason RHP"),
  mutate(Kike_postseason_away, season = "Postseason", condition = "Postseason Away"),
  mutate(Kike_posthome, season = "Postseason", condition = "Postseason Home"),
  mutate(Kike_postseason_fb, season = "Postseason", condition = "Postseason Fastball"),
  mutate(Kike_postseason_op, season = "Postseason", condition = "Postseason Other Pitches"),
  mutate(Kike_regular_fb, season = "Regular", condition = "Regular Fastball"),
  mutate(Kike_regular_op, season = "Regular", condition = "Regular Other Pitches")
)

This code combines multiple datasets on Kik Hernndezs regular-season and postseason performances into a single dataframe, adding columns for season and condition to distinguish between different conditions (pitcher handedness, game location, and pitch type). This allows for an easy comparison of his performance across various factors.

First, I compared Kike Hernndezs performance at Home vs Away in both the Postseason and Regular Season.

# Filter the data to include only Home and Away conditions for both Postseason and Regular Season
all_metrics_filtered <- all_metrics %>%
  filter(condition %in% c("Regular Home", "Regular Away", "Postseason Home", "Postseason Away"))

# Pivot all metrics into long format for easier plotting
all_metrics_long <- all_metrics_filtered %>%
  pivot_longer(cols = c(ba, slg, obp, xba, xobp, xslg),
               names_to = "metric",
               values_to = "value")



# Plot all metrics (Home vs Away for Regular and Postseason) in a single graph
ggplot(all_metrics_long, aes(x = condition, y = value, fill = season)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity", position = "dodge") +
  facet_wrap(~ metric, scales = "free_y") +  # Separate plot for each metric
  theme_minimal() +
  labs(title = "Kike Hernndez's Performance (Home vs Away) by Metric and Season",
       x = "Condition", y = "Metric Value") +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1))

This visualization provides Kike Hernandezs performance varied by home and away split between postseason and regular season. Hernandez performed very well against postseason away games (all 6 stats in the visualization shows that he performed best at postseason away games). All other stats in postseason home games, and both regular away and home games are similar.

Next, I compared Kike Hernndezs performance against Right-Handed Pitchers (RHP) and Left-Handed Pitchers (LHP) in both the Postseason and Regular Season.

# Filter the data to include only Regular and Postseason LHP and RHP
all_metrics_filtered <- all_metrics %>%
  filter(condition %in% c("Postseason LHP", "Postseason RHP", "Regular LHP", "Regular RHP"))

# Pivot all metrics into long format for easier plotting
all_metrics_long <- all_metrics_filtered %>%
  pivot_longer(cols = c(ba, slg, obp, xba, xobp, xslg),
               names_to = "metric",
               values_to = "value")

# Plot metrics comparing LHP vs RHP for both Regular Season and Postseason
ggplot(all_metrics_long, aes(x = condition, y = value, fill = condition)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity", position = "dodge") +
  facet_wrap(~ metric, scales = "free_y") +  # Separate plot for each metric
  theme_minimal() +
  labs(title = "Kike Hernndez's Performance: LHP vs RHP (Regular Season and Postseason)",
       x = "Condition", y = "Metric Value") +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1))

This visualization provides Kike Hernandezs performance during Postseason and Regular Season against pitching hand type. According to the visualization, Hernandez performed all metrics (especially ba and slg) best against right-handed pitcher during the postseason, although xobp and xslg between RHP vs LHP during the postseason are nearly identical. During the regular reason, he hits left-handed pitchers much better than right-handed pitchers. Oddly, Hernandezs stats against left-handed pitchers are slightly better than his stats against left-handed pitchers during the postseason.

Finally, this analysis compares Kike Hernndezs performance against Fastballs and Other Pitches (including Changeups, Curveballs, Sliders, etc.) in the Postseason and Regular Season.

# Check the unique values in the 'condition' column to verify the correct labels
unique(all_metrics$condition)

# Filter the data to include only Fastball and Other pitches for both Postseason and Regular Season
all_metrics_filtered <- all_metrics %>%
  filter(grepl("Fastball|Other", condition))  # Use grepl to match "Fastball" or "Other"

# Pivot all metrics into long format for easier plotting
all_metrics_long <- all_metrics_filtered %>%
  pivot_longer(cols = c(ba, slg, obp, xba, xobp, xslg),
               names_to = "metric",
               values_to = "value")

# Plot metrics comparing Fastball vs Other Pitches for both Regular Season and Postseason
ggplot(all_metrics_long, aes(x = condition, y = value, fill = condition)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity", position = "dodge") +
  facet_wrap(~ metric, scales = "free_y") +  # Separate plot for each metric
  theme_minimal() +
  labs(title = "Kike Hernndez's Performance: Fastball vs Other Pitches (Regular Season and Postseason)",
       x = "Condition", y = "Metric Value") +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1))

This visualization provides Kike Hernandezs performance split by fastball and other pitches, between postseason and regular season. According to the visualization, Hernandez hit other pitches very well during the postseason (especially slg and and xslg), despite the fact that he cannot hit other pitches during the regular season at all. In contrast, Hernandez hit fastball very similar (almost identical) both on postseason and regular season (although xobp on postseason fastball stands out tall). Especially, the slugging percentage on other pitches during the postseason really stands out tall among other situations. However, Hernandez performed better postseason stats (absolutely on other pitches, very slightly better at fastball) on every metrics.
